Gastroesophageal reflux events generally happen during relaxation of lower esophageal sphincter.

 This relaxation is a reflex that is triggered by gastric stimuli.

 The investigators hypothesize that abnormal relaxation of the gastric wall after a meal may lead to reflux events.

 To test this hypothesis, a study was designed to measure the gastric accommodation in patients undergoing esophageal impedance monitoring.

